                            <comment id="17613887" author="hiteshkhamesra" created="Fri, 7 Oct 2022 06:19:44 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;CCing &lt;a href=&quot;https://issues.apache.org/jira/secure/ViewProfile.jspa?name=noblepaul&quot; class=&quot;user-hover&quot; rel=&quot;noblepaul&quot;&gt;noblepaul&lt;/a&gt; &lt;a href=&quot;https://issues.apache.org/jira/secure/ViewProfile.jspa?name=ichattopadhyaya&quot; class=&quot;user-hover&quot; rel=&quot;ichattopadhyaya&quot;&gt;ichattopadhyaya&lt;/a&gt; &lt;a href=&quot;https://issues.apache.org/jira/secure/ViewProfile.jspa?name=jsweene2&quot; class=&quot;user-hover&quot; rel=&quot;jsweene2&quot;&gt;jsweene2&lt;/a&gt;&#160;&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="17614089" author="jsweeney" created="Fri, 7 Oct 2022 13:58:33 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;This is a bug in ZkStateWriter that can occur when using both PRS and non-PRS collections in the same cluster. The issue here is that PRS updates through overseer are not batched, but non-PRS updates are batched. When using both PRS and non-PRS in the same cluster, a PRS collection update through overseer will be immediately written to ZK and will reset the counters that control when to flush batched updates without actually flushing the batched updates. The result is that updates that were batched can be skipped entirely.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;I am opening a PR now that will fix this by not resetting the batch counters when immediately writing a PRS update.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
